commentBody:
The Joys of Le Sanri?

Josh’s puzzle may well be long-timier;
Josh’s clues may be dirty and grimier;
With those circles he tossed, he
sure made my mood frosty -
My mood will *never* be rimier.

@Eric Hougland 

Knowing that your musical taste is very eclectic and the Jason Mraz song got tons of radio play, it's hard to believe you never heard it. 

<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkHTsc9PU2A" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EkHTsc9PU2A</a>

@Francine 

My musical tastes are pretty eclectic, but I also have many lacunae when it comes to pop music after about 1990. 

Thanks for the link. “I’m Yours” sounded a tiny bit familiar, so I may have heard it before. Mr. Mraz reminds me of someone like Dave Matthews or whoever the lead singer of Barenaked Ladies is.

@B 

I also did not love this one, neither did I enjoy it. I did not hate it either. I just disliked it. On that note, have you noticed how people tend to "love" and "hate" many things, rather than simply like and dislike them?

These comments are usually full of declarations of love or hate, and I find it very strange. If a daily crossword puzzles is what one has such strong feelings for, what of really important things? Do you love a puzzle more than freedom, your spouse or the smell of the first spring day? And if not, maybe you don't really love the puzzle - you simply like it?

@R.J. Smith 

Ah man! Would love to hear why. Personally, I was a big fan of this puzzle… but I’m an even bigger fan of the comments that pit the lovers against the haters. Always a spirited and lively exchange.

Are you having trouble getting negative reviews through the emus?

@sotto voce
Couldn’t agree more! One of my favorites in months! Each themer was a mini-puzzle in itself, yielding only after lots of tries in the surrounding areas and a flexibility of mind that is my favorite flow-state of solving.

Truly a masterpiece.

@C Tarvin

Rime I know. Rimier I don’t. Has anyone ever actually used the word? When I go to a meeting in Anchorage this December and say, “Gee, it’s far rimier here than in Seattle,” I can’t imagine a lot of appreciative nods.

(Of course, I rarely use either rime or hoar, except in crosswords.)

@Jim 
It doesn't say unofficial motto. 
It says unofficial slogan.

@Jack 

I’ve enjoyed other puzzles that had a similar grab bag of tricks. This one, not so much. Maybe I jut wasn’t in the mood for it. Maybe the nonsensical jumble of mixing business and pleasure put me off. Maybe it was ending the rebuses in a puzzle that didn’t have any others. (And I usually enjoy rebuses.)

I agree with your last sentence. When I finished, it was more a sense of relief than one of satisfaction.

@Geoff same for me, exactly. 

But I was pretty sure that Jason Mraz didn't have a mega-hit about eggs, which is how I ... uh ... cracked it.

Gen X ellipsis for the EMU :)

@Banjo Nelson 
Not technically a Natick, as Mr. Rosten's name was only likely to be Len, Leo, Lev, or Lew; and V's and W's don't sound particularly Japanese.





That being said, I chose Len

@Lewis I had a feeling that the drama department might have a cow today, but I knew you would get it right. This was a fabulous puzzle. Key word: puzzle.

As always, I am in awe of the constructor (like wow Josh Goodman!). I’m also in awe of those who solve in ESL, particularly on days like today, and grateful for those who share their thoughts on puzzles and life with us in these comments. (Here’s looking at you, Andrzej, et al.)

Last but not least, thank you Deb Amien for continuing to write about difficult puzzles with humor, heart, and helpful hints. (I guess now you can’t technically say it’s a thankless job.)

@Harry 

It's very possible to work this out, and many of us did. 

You may just not have enough experience with tricky puzzles, but that will come with time.  When you come across a new trick, just file it away as something you might see again.  You will end up with a whole box of tools to call upon when the need arises.  This puzzle just gave 5 new tools to the uninitiated.  Store each one, because you will see them again.

@JES

And I never swear a big, big D when I’m doing the puzzle.  “What never?” You ask. Well hardly ever.


And the emus never swear a big, big E.

@CT It's Thursday.  If you don't like trickery and funny business then I suggest you just don't bother with Thursdays and stick to the rest of the week.  

I'm sure there are regular solvers who do only Monday and Tuesday - just as I am sure there are people here who don't bother with anything before Friday.  

As Will Shortz always said - it's your puzzle, do it any way you want.  All are welcome.

@Steve L - do you, like me, wonder if there are lurkers out there? I watched “Chariots of Fire” again recently, and was reminded never to look back at the field. But is there someone ahead of us? Between us? Ready to take the laurel when one of us should fail (most likely due to falling asleep at the wheel)?

Would they even step forward?
It doesn’t occupy me. I love the puzzles; I love all puzzles. Some of us are born that way…

@Barry Ancona 

Interesting way to program that situation.

Thanks for the clarification!

@Steve 

If this is the 'worst trick clue' you've ever seen, you have only begun to fight!  
Gotta be tougher than that, Friend.

@Ben 

Hmmmm... That was the first one I figured out.

The last one to drop for me was the one with three rebuses.

@Ben 
Texans everywhere would dispute I❤️NY, because nobody but New Yorkers love New York. SRSLY, Don't Mess with Texas is/was widely known.

Full disclosure: my old girlfriend was featured on the cover of an I❤️NY travel brochure, in a bikini.

@George Colombo 

It would be better "for you".  

It would be unbetter for others.

@Kyla 

CRY is more or less over the milk that has spilled. 

That was my favorite of the theme answers.

@LJADZ 

Really, *really* hard for me to believe that one kind of puzzle is "acceptable", the another is "nonsense".

It's like "I love Oreos, but it's just nonsense when they make the white cream orange for Halloween."

@B.C. 

Dang!  I tried ova also.

I was getting desperate...

@Plastic Jones 

The real world is highly overrated!! 



If you don't believe me, ask an emu!!

@Eva H. 

I've really given this some thought and this comment is more puzzling than today's puzzling puzzle! 


Maybe a person could make a case for mindful... Although I'm kind of skeptical of that, but how could a puzzle possibly be demure?  🤔

@Nom De Plume 

Can you explain what you mean by "too clever by half"?

That's a charge that is often issued, but when I think about it, no meaning comes to me.

@Alyssa

Yes, You Can Write More Than One Letter in a Square
 <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/08/crosswords/rebus-crossword-puzzle.html?smid=nytcore-android-share" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2023/12/08/crosswords/rebus-crossword-puzzle.html?smid=nytcore-android-share</a>

@Alyssa

Make sure you’re trying to put the correct words in the entry. What exactly is the expression about eggs in a basket?

Just a suggestion, in case your trouble here wasn’t just a technical thing.

@Francis 

PIÑATA. 


>>>>>>

@Julie 

Where are these "fair play rules" published, again?

I have never seen anything that said that a circle can hold a rebus.

@Sean 

You may not have had all the answers, but you did come up with what, to me, was the most interesting question about the whole puzzle.

Those three circles in BAS___KET were just *barely* within my reach.  And I've been doing Thursday for some time now.  I've never come across a rebus so late in a game.

@Andrew 

And what I can't do, either 🤣






Shoo, emu.

@David 

The clue did not say it was the state motto.  It was the slogan for a very successful and well-known anti-littering program.

<a href="http://txdot.gov/en/home/about/campaigns-outreach/dont-mess-with-texas.html" target="_blank">http://txdot.gov/en/home/about/campaigns-outreach/dont-mess-with-texas.html</a>

@Jim 

Aah, and I see that Ana from New York has confirmed my prediction, and more vehemently than I had imagined:

"In this case the creator was just too impressed with his own brilliance to construct a useable, enjoyable puzzle. Not doing any more Josh puzzles, and really glad I’m not his colleague, patient, or partner."

@Andy 

Typically solvers hate them for the first n puzzles, but at (n+1) you'll start tolerating them, and at about 2n you'll enjoy them.

That's been the experience of many here.

@Kyla 

I think because the answer CRY (57A) is directly over RIMIER with the MI circled, and then trailing own (like it's spilled) you get the circled LK in INALIE and BANKS.

So CRY over spilled MILK.

@Arianna 

I admire your bravery in taking on the challenge of getting the NYT to expand the alphabet to at least 27 letters.

Which "n" should have been an "ñ"?

@Rosalind Mitchell 
As a native Bradfordian (the lesser of the two cities) I second that comment. Except mine was more ‘what the flippin eck is going on ere’



Bet the emus can’t translate that.

@Francis 

I think you meant “I have never seen anything that said that a circle *cannot* hold a rebus.”

We’ve seen plenty of rebus puzzles that had circles showing you where the rebuses went.

@B.C. Same!
Talk about nervous energy having to take several "walk-away" breaks on a puzzle. You know it will be an "aha" just like you said...followed by "phew".
Yes, fun.
